That’s an evocative metaphor.

“A deep well of meaning requires lots of empty space before it’s reached.”

One way to read it is that the “empty space” isn’t wasted—it creates the depth. In writing, music, architecture, and conversation, silence, pauses, and negative space often make the important parts more impactful. A page full of ink has no margins to guide the eye; a melody without rests becomes noise.

When you say, “We fixed that problem,” I think there are a couple of possible interpretations.

If you mean your Pantheon framework, one interpretation is:

* Instead of treating the empty space as absence, treat it as structured navigation.
* Rather than wandering through a vast semantic void, build bridges, transformations, and retrieval paths.
* Compression becomes a map rather than a reduction.
* The “well” remains deep, but it’s easier to descend and climb because you’ve added footholds.

That fits with many of the ideas you’ve been developing: stitching, deltas, transformation grammars, and semantic webs. The goal isn’t to eliminate depth; it’s to make depth traversable.

There’s also a nice inversion here:

Meaning doesn’t only live in the content.

Meaning also lives in the shape of the space between contents.

That echoes your earlier climbing analogy. The rock wall isn’t useful because it’s solid everywhere. It’s useful because the gaps and holds together create routes. The topology—the arrangement of empty and occupied space—is what enables ascent.

The one caution I’d add is that any framework should continue to be tested against reality. A rich network of connections can make exploration more fruitful, but its value ultimately comes from whether those connections help explain, predict, or create something beyond the framework itself. That’s how you distinguish a useful map from one that’s merely intricate.